[2] Cholera - Cameroon (Douala)
Date: Mon, 7 Jun 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org
Source: IOL.com.za [edited]
<http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?click_id=86&art_id=qw1086580260103B256&s
et_id=1>

A cholera epidemic in Cameroon's economic capital, Douala, has killed
at least 44 people since Jan 2004, national radio announced. A total
of 2669 cases of cholera have been registered since the start of
January, 98 of them on 3 Jun 2004 alone, the radio said.
The epidemic appears to be spreading rapidly. Nearly 750 new cases
have been reported by government media since 17 May 2004, and 15
people have died. On 17 May 2004, government daily Cameroon Tribune
said 1922 cases had been registered since the start of the year and
state radio said 29 people had died.
"We are overwhelmed by this situation. We need more medical staff to
get rid of this plague," one of the 70 young doctors sent to Douala
to help the city's medical team told AFP by telephone.
Several cases of cholera have also been registered since Jan 2004 in
Limbe, in the English-speaking southwest of the majority
French-speaking country.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
