[3] Cholera - Mozambique
Date: Mon, 7 Jun 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com & Agencia de Informacao de Mocambique [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200406070920.html>

Cholera Epidemic Coming to an End
------------------------------------
The Mozambican health authorities say that the cholera epidemic that
has been raging in parts of the country since December 2004 has come
under control, thanks both to the onset of winter and the improvement
of sanitation conditions in some urban centers.
Maputo city health director Olivia Ferreira, cited in the Mon 7 Jun
2004 issue of the daily paper "Noticias", said that the Cholera
Treatment Center (CTC) at the Mavalane General Hospital is currently
receiving only 2 or 3 patients a day, compared with more than 300 a
day at the peak of the epidemic. Only 5 patients were still under
medical care at the center by late Sun 6 Jun 2004. During the first
3 to 4 months of this year, the Mavalane CTC were always treating
more than 100 patients at a time.
Since the outbreak of the disease in Maputo, during the 1st week of
December 2003, the Mavalane CTC has treated about 12 000 patients,
with 40 deaths, all from Maputo city.
In the central province of Sofala, the 2nd most affected by the
disease, with more than 5000 cases and 32 deaths since January 2004,
the situation is also reported as calm.
--
