[5] Diarrhea, waterborne - Pakistan (Sindh) (02)
Date: Mon, 7 Jun 2004 11:11:00 -0400
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <arodriguezm@saludfmv.org>
Source: Yahoo News, UK [edited]
<http://uk.news.yahoo.com/040607/323/eve3z.html>

In southern Sindh province contaminated water has caused the deaths of
38 people, mostly children, a minister said.
Tainted water in Hyderabad city, home to 3.6 million people, 160
kilometers (100 miles) northeast of Karachi, has claimed 38 lives
over the past month, while more than 4000 people reported
gastroenteritis problems.
"At least 32 children and 6 adults have so far died of water-related
diseases," chief of Hyderabad's Civil Hospital Hadi Bux Jatoi said.
The problem began when provincial irrigation authorities released
water from overflowing Manchar Lake, 130 kilometers (81 miles)
northwest of Hyderabad, into thr Indus River, the key source of the
city's water supply.
Officials said scores of people suffering from diarrhea, cholera and
other water-borne diseases had been rushing to the 2 public and
private hospitals daily ever since the problem erupted.
Water quality seems to have improved with emergency measures and
gradual replacement of water reservoirs with new ones. "Now the water
quality is better and the incidence of water-related diseases is receding,"
Ishtiaq said.
